      مُهَدَّبٌ Having an unwoven end, or extremity;
syn. ذُو هُدَّابٍ: occurring as an epithet applied to
the kind of stuff called دِمَقْسٌ. (TA.)


      6 
      تهاربوا (S, O, K, art. فر,) They fled, one
from another. (TK.)


      مُهَرَّتٌ: see هَرِيتٌ.  
    -A2-  Flesh-meat thoroughly
cooked, so that it has fallen in pieces; as also مُهَرَّدٌ;
or this latter [only] is the correct word. (TA,
from a trad.)


      هِلْبَوْثٌ Stupid; foolish; of little sense: or dull
of speech and understanding; doltish; heavy;
syn. فَدْمٌ. (S, and some copies of the K.)


      هَنَبٌ [probably an inf. n., of which the verb
is هَنِبَ, aor. 

      هَنَبَ,] Weakness of understanding;
want of discrimination; stupidity; foolishness;
littleness of sense. (S.)


      هَائِدٌ Returning (Msb) [from evil to good or
from good to evil: see 1:] repenting and returning to the truth: (S, L:) pl. هُودٌ, (S, A, L, Msb,)
like as بُزْلٌ is pl. of بَازِلٌ. (S, L, Msb.)


      مَهِيضٌ A bone broken after having become set;
(S, A, K;) as also ↓ مُهْتَاضٌ (S) and ↓ مُنْهَاضٌ.
(S, A.)
